{{infobox religious building |name=Uchima Udun |image=File:Agari Udun, Uchima Udun at Nishihara 202410.jpg|thumb|caption=Agari Udun, part of Uchima Udun }}
'''Uchima Udun''' (内間御殿) is a sacred site in {{ill|Nishihara, Okinawa|ja|西原町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nakagami District, Okinawa|ja|中頭郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was designated a [[Historic Site of Japan|National Historic Site]] on [[February 7, 2011]] (Heisei 23).
== Overview == Uchima Udun was established in [[1666]], 190 years after the death of {{ill|King Shō En|ja|尚円王|12=draft|12=draft}}, the founder of the {{ill|Second Shō Dynasty|ja|第二尚氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was built on the former residence of Kanamaru (later King Shō En) when he was appointed chieftain of Uchima<ref name="report">Nishihara Town Board of Education (2012). "Uchima Udun: National Designation Symposium Report," pp. 3-5</ref><ref name="choshi4">Nishihara Town History Compilation Committee (1989). "Nishihara Town History, Volume 4: Folklore of Nishihara," Nishihara Town Office, pp. 260-261</ref>. Uchima Udun consists of the {{ill|Seie Udun|ja|西江御殿|12=draft|12=draft}} to the north and the {{ill|Agari Udun|ja|東江御殿|12=draft|12=draft}} to the south<ref name="choshi5">Nishihara Town History Compilation Committee (1999). "Nishihara Town History, Volume 5: Archaeological Materials of Nishihara," Nishihara Town Office, pp. 169-170</ref>.
Kanamaru was a vassal of {{ill|Prince Gushichan|ja|越来王子|12=draft|12=draft}} (later {{ill|King Shō Taikyū|ja|尚泰久王|12=draft|12=draft}}) and was appointed chieftain of Uchima in [[1454]]<ref name="report" />. During this time, he took the younger sister of Kamuta Shinmuta of Kadekaru as a concubine<ref name="choshi4"></ref>. As a result, the former residence of Kanamaru came to be called {{ill|Ōdonuchi|ja|大殿内|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="report" />.
== Location == * Uchima Udun is located at 42-1, 50, and 51 Uenomatsu, Kadekaru, Nishihara Town, Nakagami District, Okinawa Prefecture.
== History == === Establishment === In 1666, on the advice of the then-[[Regent (Japan)|Regent]] {{ill|Haneji Chōshū|ja|羽地朝秀|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōken), a thatched {{ill|Kirizuma-zukuri|ja|切妻造|12=draft|12=draft}} shrine (2 ken × 3 ken) called Agari Udun was built at the site of the Ōdonuchi residence<ref name="report" />. At this time, a {{ill|celadon|ja|青磁|12=draft|12=draft}} pillow was enshrined as the sacred object<ref name="choshi5" />. Originally, Agari Udun was surrounded by bamboo fencing rather than stone walls<ref name="choshi4" />.
=== Designation as a Sacred Site by the Royal Government === In [[1689]], the {{ill|Ōmii Udun|ja|大美御殿|12=draft|12=draft}}, the government office overseeing Ryukyuan royal rituals, reconstructed the damaged Agari Udun using oak wood and converted it into a tiled shrine<ref name="report" /><ref name="choshi4" />. This officially recognized Uchima Udun as a sacred site connected to the Ryukyu Kingdom, leading to further government maintenance<ref name="report" />.
In [[1706]], the residents of Nishihara Magiri built a thatched shrine (3 ken × 2.5 ken) north of Uchima Udun, later known as "Seie Udun."
=== Theft of the Treasure Pillow and Fortification === In [[1735]], the treasured sacred pillow was stolen. In response, the following year ([[1736]]), the bamboo fencing was replaced with stone walls, and main and side gates were installed, featuring [[bolt (fastener)|bolt locks]]. The shrine was also tiled<ref name="choshi4" /><ref name="choshi5" />.
In [[1737]], Seie Udun was also converted into a tiled structure, with bamboo fencing added around its perimeter<ref name="report" />.
In [[1738]], King {{ill|Shō Kei|ja|尚敬王|12=draft|12=draft}} inscribed the plaque "Chiwa" (致和), which was placed above the main gate of Agari Udun<ref name="bunkazai">Nishihara Town Board of Education (2013). "Cultural Properties of Nishihara Town," pp. 6-7</ref>. A stone monument called "Monument of the Former Residence of the Late King" (先王旧宅碑), detailing the history of the renovation, was erected in the inner courtyard<ref name="choshi4" />.
=== The Battle of Okinawa and Restoration === During the final stages of [[World War II]] in [[1945]], both shrines were destroyed in the [[Battle of Okinawa]], and the "Monument of the Former Residence of the Late King" was partially damaged by shellfire<ref name="report" />.
In [[1951]], donations from the {{ill|Ōya Monchu|ja|大屋門中|12=draft|12=draft}} (descendants of the Ōdonuchi family) and Ryukyuan emigrants to [[Hawaii]] led to the reconstruction of Agari Udun with a corrugated iron-roofed shrine<ref name="report" />. Seie Udun was reconstructed in thatched form by the {{ill|Irei Monchu|ja|伊礼門中|12=draft|12=draft}}, the original caretakers of the site<ref name="report" /><ref name="choshi4" />.
In [[1960]], Agari Udun was renovated into a wooden structure with a corrugated iron roof (2 ken × 2 ken)<ref name="report" />. In [[1974]], it was rebuilt in its current form using concrete blocks (2 ken × 2.5 ken) by Masao Nakayama, the head of the Ōya Monchu<ref name="bunkazai" /><ref name="choshi4" />.
== The Sacred Pillow == In 1735, thieves broke into Agari Udun and stole the treasured sacred pillow. King Shō Kei personally led his retainers in searching for the item, ultimately recovering it from a rice field<ref name="bunkazai" />.
However, in [[1842]], another burglary occurred, and the sacred pillow was stolen once again, never to be recovered<ref name="report" />. As a result, in [[1835]], a celadon dish enshrined in Seie Udun was designated as the new sacred object of Agari Udun<ref name="report" /><ref name="choshi4" />.
== References == {{Reflist}}
== See also == * [[List of Historic Sites of Kyushu and Okinawa]]
